narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Learned how to work with bacteria in a biochemistry context (sterile technique, transformation, kinetics determinations)
Skills in a biochemistry lab and techniques in genetic engineering at the molecular level.
Learned about all the laboratory procedures to go from designing mutant proteins to actually isolating these proteins and doing assays on them.
I learn a lot of useful biochemical techniques that I learned about in my courses. I found this class incredibly helpful in ensuring accuracy.
Pipetting, DNA/plasmid transformation, SDS page, kinetics assay, Michelis Menten constants

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: very low pressure and professors are amazing and want you to learn! Great intro class if you havent worked in a lab

Weaknesses: sometimes a little unclear as to what we are supposed to be doing during lab time

Strengths: fairly straight-forward with what was expected of us/what we were supposed to be doing. The workload was good in that it was not excessive.
Weaknesses: sometimes felt a little disorganized, but not to the point of confusion.

Strengths: very reasonable workload and straightforward material
Weakness: although the workload is reasonable, it is very back-loaded and many of the major assignments are due towards the end of the term

Strengths - clear lab manual
Weaknesses - overall objective of lab can be lost over the weeks with all the different experiments without unifying discussion

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes I would totally recommend this course to another MCDB or MBB major that needs a lab credit!
Yes, the workload isn't too bad and the material is interesting.
Yes, if the need to take a biology/biochemistry lab.
Yes definitely if you're learning intro lab techniques and science communication is covered at the end!
